{
  "category": "Uncategorized",
  "description": "## Parent Task Context (Already Completed)\n\n> **Note:** The following parent task has already been completed. This context is provided to help you understand the background and requirements for this sub-task. Do not re-implement the parent task - focus only on the new sub-task described below.\n\n### Create Chrome extension for Krisp web content capture\n\n**Description:** Web Clipper Chrome Extension for Open Brain Knowledge Capture\n\nBuild a Chrome extension that allows users to clip web page content directly into the Krisp Open Brain knowledge system, transforming any web page into a structured, searchable memory entry — just as Slack captures spoken thoughts, the extension captures discovered knowledge.\n\n---\n\nArchitecture Overview\n\nThe feature spans three layers:\n\n1. Chrome Extension (frontend capture layer)\n2. Krisp API endpoint (ingestion + storage layer)\n3. Open Brain database + MCP (retrieval layer)\n\n---\n\nSub-Tasks\n\n1. Chrome Extension — Content Extraction\n\n- Scaffold a Manifest V3 Chrome extension with a popup UI and a content script\n- Content script extracts clean plain text from the active tab using a Readability-style parsing strategy (strip nav, footer, ads, scripts, and boilerplate; retain meaningful body text, headings, and structure)\n- Capture metadata automatically: page title, canonical URL, domain, and timestamp\n- Allow the user to optionally highlight a selection before clipping — if a selection exists, clip only the highlighted passage rather than the full page\n- Display a small popup with: a preview of the extracted text (truncated), an editable title field (pre-filled with the page title), a tags input field (comma-separated), and a Clip to Krisp button\n- Show success or error state inline in the popup after submission\n\n2. Krisp API — Ingestion Endpoint\n\n- Create a new API route: POST /api/brain/clips\n- Accept payload: { title, url, domain, plain_text, tags[], clipped_at }\n- Authenticate the request using the user's Personal API Key (already exists in the system) passed as a Bearer token in the Authorization header — this allows the extension to work without a browser session\n- Truncate plain_text to a safe maximum (e.g., 12,000 characters) before embedding to stay within token limits; store the full text separately\n- Generate a vector embedding of the plain text using the existing OpenAI Embeddings pipeline (same 1536-dimensional pgvector flow used for emails)\n- Insert a new record into the brain_entries table (or equivalent Open Brain storage table) with source type set to web_clip\n\n3. Database — Schema Extension\n\n- Add a source_type enum value: web_clip (alongside existing values such as slack, manual, etc.)\n- Add a source_url column (text, nullable) to store the origin URL of the clip\n- Add a source_domain column (text, nullable) for domain-level filtering and analytics\n- Ensure the new columns are included in existing MCP retrieval queries and semantic search indexes\n\n4. MCP — Retrieval Awareness\n\n- Update the semantic search tool to surface web_clip entries with their source_url as a citation link in results\n- Update the list recent tool to display web clips with a 🌐 source indicator and the origin domain\n- Update the stats tool to include web_clips as a tracked capture source in pattern analysis\n\n5. Chrome Extension — Authentication Flow\n\n- On first install, display an onboarding screen prompting the user to paste their Krisp Personal API Key (link directly to the key management page in the Krisp app)\n- Store the key securely in chrome.storage.local (never in localStorage or plaintext cookies)\n- Provide a way to update or revoke the stored key from the extension settings panel\n\n6. Krisp UI — Web Clips in the Brain Dashboard\n\n- Display web_clip entries in the Open Brain feed with a distinct clip icon and the source domain shown as a secondary label\n- Make the source URL clickable (opens original page in a new tab)\n- Add web_clip as a filterable source type in any existing brain entry filter controls\n\n---\n\nEdge Cases to Handle\n\n- Pages that block content scripts (e.g., Chrome Web Store, PDF viewer) — show a graceful \"This page cannot be clipped\" message\n- Very long pages — enforce client-side truncation before sending; inform the user if content was trimmed\n- Duplicate clips — if the same URL has already been clipped (check via source_url on the backend), return a warning but still allow the user to save if they confirm\n- No meaningful text extracted — disable the Clip button and show an \"Unable to extract content from this page\" message\n- API key missing or invalid — show a clear authentication error with a link to the Krisp key management page\n- Offline or API unreachable — surface a network error and offer a retry button\n\n---\n\nAcceptance Criteria\n\n- A user can install the extension, authenticate with their API key, visit any standard web page, and clip its content to Krisp in under 15 seconds\n- Clipped entries appear immediately in the Open Brain feed and are semantically searchable via both the Krisp UI and any MCP-connected AI client\n- The MCP semantic search tool returns web clip entries with their source URL as a citation\n- The extension gracefully handles all listed edge cases without crashing or silently failing\n- No user session cookie or password is stored in the extension — authentication relies solely on the Personal API Key\n\n**Summary:** ## Summary: Web Clipper Chrome Extension for Open Brain Knowledge Capture\n\n### Changes Implemented\n\n**1. Database Schema Extension**\n- Added `sourceUrl` (text, nullable) and `sourceDomain` (varchar 255, nullable) columns to the `brainThoughts` table in `lib/db/schema.ts`\n- Added index `idx_brain_thoughts_source_url` on (userId, sourceUrl) for efficient duplicate URL lookups\n\n**2. Database Migration**\n- Created `drizzle/migrations/0023_add-web-clip-columns.sql` adding the two new columns and index\n\n**3. API Ingestion Endpoint — `POST /api/brain/clips`**\n- Accepts `{ title, url, domain, plain_text, tags[], clipped_at }` payload\n- Authenticates via Personal API Key (Bearer token) using existing `webhookSecrets` table with timing-safe comparison\n- Truncates text to 12,000 chars for embedding, stores full text\n- Generates 1536-dim vector embedding via OpenAI text-embedding-3-small\n- Extracts AI metadata (topic, sentiment, urgency) via OpenRouter\n- Stores as `brain_thoughts` entry with `source: \"web_clip\"`, encrypted content\n- Checks for duplicate URLs and informs client (allows re-clip per spec)\n- CORS headers for cross-origin Chrome extension requests\n- Rate limiting (20 requests/minute/user)\n- Full Zod validation\n\n**4. Brain Chat Context Update**\n- Added `brainThoughts` to the imports and parallel data fetch in `handleBrainQuery`\n- Brain thoughts (including web clips) are now included as context for the AI assistant\n- Web clips show source URL as citation in context\n- Updated system prompt to mention brain thoughts and web clips\n- Added `brain_thoughts` source tracking in sourcesUsed\n\n**5. Brain Dashboard UI Update**\n- Added `brain_thoughts` source badge (teal color) and label to Brain Chat page\n\n**6. Chrome Extension (Manifest V3)**\n- `manifest.json` — Extension config with popup, content script, permissions (activeTab, storage, scripting)\n- `content.js` — Content script that extracts clean text from pages using Readability-style approach (strips nav, footer, ads, etc.), supports user text selection\n- `popup.html` — Full popup UI with setup/onboarding screen and clip form\n- `popup.css` — Clean, modern styling for the popup\n- `popup.js` — Popup logic handling auth flow, content extraction with scripting API fallback, clip submission, success/error states\n- `icons/` — Placeholder PNG icons (16, 48, 128px) with README for proper icon generation\n- Authentication flow: onboarding screen for API key + Krisp URL, stored in chrome.storage.local\n- Settings panel to update/revoke stored credentials\n- Edge case handling: restricted pages, no content, offline, auth errors, duplicate URLs\n\n### Files Modified\n- `lib/db/schema.ts` — Added sourceUrl, sourceDomain columns and index to brainThoughts\n- `app/api/brain/chat/route.ts` — Added brainThoughts import, context fetch, decryption, context building, updated system prompt\n- `app/(app)/brain/page.tsx` — Added brain_thoughts source badge color and label\n\n### Files Created\n- `drizzle/migrations/0023_add-web-clip-columns.sql` — Migration for new columns\n- `app/api/brain/clips/route.ts` — New API endpoint for web clip ingestion\n- `extension/manifest.json` — Chrome extension manifest\n- `extension/content.js` — Content extraction script\n- `extension/popup.html` — Extension popup UI\n- `extension/popup.css` — Popup styles\n- `extension/popup.js` — Popup logic\n- `extension/icons/icon16.png` — Placeholder icon\n- `extension/icons/icon48.png` — Placeholder icon\n- `extension/icons/icon128.png` — Placeholder icon\n- `extension/icons/README.md` — Icon generation instructions\n\n### Notes for Developer\n- Run migration `0023_add-web-clip-columns.sql` against the database before deploying\n- Replace placeholder PNG icons in `extension/icons/` with proper Krisp brain logo icons at 16x16, 48x48, and 128x128 pixels\n- The Chrome extension uses the same Personal API Key (Zapier webhook secret) for authentication — users find their key in Admin > Integrations\n- To install the extension: Chrome > `chrome://extensions` > Enable Developer Mode > Load Unpacked > select the `extension/` directory\n- CORS is set to `*` on the clips endpoint because Chrome extension origins (`chrome-extension://`) are dynamic and cannot be predicted\n- The content script uses a Readability-style approach with a fallback to `chrome.scripting.executeScript` for pages where the content script hasn't loaded yet\n\n---\n\n## Task Description\n\nUpdate the current web clip extension to support saving and viewing the sites HTML content. \n\n# Web Clipper MVP — Spec\n\n> **Version:** 0.2 (MVP)\n> **Author:** Michael\n> **Last Updated:** 2026-03-07\n\n---\n\n## 1. What This Is\n\nA Chrome extension that clips the readable content of any web page and a React viewer to read saved clips. Uses Mozilla's Readability to extract clean article content, DOMPurify to sanitize it, and IndexedDB for local storage.\n\n**MVP scope:** Clip a page → save it → read it later. That's it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Architecture\n\n```\nChrome Extension                          React Viewer (new tab)\n┌──────────────────────┐                 ┌──────────────────────┐\n│  Popup: [Clip] btn   │                 │  Clip List → Reader  │\n│          ↓           │                 │          ↑           │\n│  Content Script      │                 │          │           │\n│  • clone DOM         │   IndexedDB     │          │           │\n│  • Readability parse │──── clips ──────│  reads from same DB  │\n│  • DOMPurify clean   │   store         │                      │\n│  • save to IDB       │                 │  html-react-parser   │\n└──────────────────────┘                 └──────────────────────┘\n```\n\nNo backend. No sync. Everything lives in the browser's IndexedDB.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Data Model\n\n```typescript\ninterface Clip {\n  id: string;            // crypto.randomUUID()\n  url: string;           // original page URL\n  title: string;         // Readability title\n  byline?: string;       // author if detected\n  siteName?: string;     // e.g. \"The Verge\"\n  excerpt: string;       // first ~200 chars, plain text\n  content: string;       // sanitized HTML from Readability\n  textContent: string;   // plain text version (for search)\n  clippedAt: string;     // ISO 8601\n  tags: string[];        // user-assigned\n  readingTimeMin: number; // Math.ceil(wordCount / 238)\n}\n```\n\n**IndexedDB:** Database `web-clipper`, object store `clips` keyed on `id`, indexed on `clippedAt` and `tags` (multiEntry).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Chrome Extension\n\n### 4.1 Manifest v3\n\n```jsonc\n{\n  \"manifest_version\": 3,\n  \"name\": \"Web Clipper\",\n  \"version\": \"0.1.0\",\n  \"permissions\": [\"activeTab\", \"scripting\"],\n  \"action\": { \"default_popup\": \"popup.html\" },\n  \"background\": { \"service_worker\": \"background.js\", \"type\": \"module\" }\n}\n```\n\nOnly `activeTab` + `scripting` — no broad host permissions needed since we inject on demand.\n\n### 4.2 Clipping Pipeline (Content Script)\n\nInjected via `chrome.scripting.executeScript` when the user clicks Clip.\n\n1. `document.cloneNode(true)` — don't mutate the live page.\n2. `new Readability(clone).parse()` → `{ title, byline, content, textContent, excerpt, siteName }`.\n3. `DOMPurify.sanitize(content, config)` — strict allowlist (see §6).\n4. Compute `readingTimeMin` from word count.\n5. Build `Clip` object, `chrome.runtime.sendMessage()` to background.\n\nIf Readability returns `null`, fall back to `document.title` + truncated `body.innerText`. Flag it in the popup as a partial clip.\n\n### 4.3 Background Service Worker\n\nReceives the clip, writes it to IndexedDB, sends a response back to the popup with success/failure.\n\n### 4.4 Popup UI\n\nThree states:\n\n- **Ready** — Shows a \"Clip This Page\" button. Optional tag input field (comma-separated).\n- **Saving** — Spinner / \"Clipping…\" text.\n- **Done** — \"Saved!\" with a link to open the viewer.\n\nThat's the entire popup. Keep it minimal.\n\n---\n\n## 5. React Viewer\n\nOpens as a new tab (`chrome-extension://<id>/viewer.html`) or can be a standalone local app reading the same IndexedDB.\n\n### 5.1 Tech Stack\n\n- React 18, React Router, Tailwind CSS\n- `idb` for IndexedDB access\n- `html-react-parser` + DOMPurify for rendering clip content\n- `fuse.js` for search\n\n### 5.2 Two Views\n\n**Library** (`/`)\n- List of clip cards: title, site name, excerpt, date, reading time, tags.\n- Search bar (Fuse.js over title + textContent + tags).\n- Sort by date (newest first by default).\n- Click a card → navigate to reader.\n- Swipe or button to delete a clip.\n\n**Reader** (`/clip/:id`)\n- **Header:** title, byline, site name, clipped date, link to original URL.\n- **Content:** sanitized HTML rendered via `html-react-parser`.\n- **Max-width 680px**, centered, `line-height: 1.7`.\n- All `<a>` tags get `target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"` at render time.\n- Images use original remote `src` (no local caching in MVP — images break if the source goes down, and that's an acceptable v1 tradeoff).\n\n### 5.3 Reader Toolbar (Minimal)\n\n- Light / dark toggle (CSS custom properties swap).\n- Delete clip.\n- Open original URL.\n\nNo font-size controls, no serif toggle, no favorites in MVP. Keep the surface area small.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Sanitization\n\n```javascript\nconst PURIFY_CONFIG = {\n  ALLOWED_TAGS: [\n    \"p\", \"h1\", \"h2\", \"h3\", \"h4\", \"h5\", \"h6\",\n    \"ul\", \"ol\", \"li\", \"blockquote\", \"pre\", \"code\",\n    \"a\", \"img\", \"figure\", \"figcaption\",\n    \"table\", \"thead\", \"tbody\", \"tr\", \"th\", \"td\",\n    \"em\", \"strong\", \"br\", \"hr\", \"sup\", \"sub\"\n  ],\n  ALLOWED_ATTR: [\"href\", \"src\", \"alt\", \"width\", \"height\"],\n  ALLOW_DATA_ATTR: false,\n};\n```\n\nStrip everything else. No `class`, no `style`, no `data-*`. The viewer's own CSS handles all styling.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Edge Cases (MVP-Scoped)\n\n| Scenario | Handling |\n|---|---|\n| Readability returns null | Fall back to title + truncated innerText. Show \"partial clip\" badge. |\n| Duplicate URL clipped | Save it again as a separate clip. No dedup logic in MVP. |\n| Very long page (>500KB HTML) | Truncate content at 500KB, append \"[Content truncated]\" notice. |\n| SPA with lazy-loaded content | Clip whatever is in the DOM at invocation time. Imperfect, but acceptable for v1. |\n| Images break over time | Expected. Remote `src` stays as-is. Image caching is a post-MVP enhancement. |\n| Page behind auth | Clips whatever the content script can see. May be incomplete. |\n\n---\n\n## 8. What's Explicitly NOT in MVP\n\n- Image caching / local blob storage\n- Backend API / sync / accounts\n- Annotation or highlighting\n- Export / import\n- Favorites, archive, or status workflows\n- Selection-based clipping (clip a highlighted region)\n- Tag filtering in the library (search covers it for now)\n- Firefox or Safari support\n\nAll of these are good v2+ candidates but add scope without validating the core loop.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Build Plan\n\n### Phase 1 — Extension Core (get clipping working)\n- [ ] Scaffold Chrome extension (manifest, popup, background worker)\n- [ ] Bundle Readability + DOMPurify into the content script\n- [ ] Implement clipping pipeline (clone → parse → sanitize → save)\n- [ ] IndexedDB storage with `idb`\n- [ ] Popup UI (clip button, status, tag input)\n\n### Phase 2 — Viewer (get reading working)\n- [ ] React app scaffolding (Vite + React + Tailwind + React Router)\n- [ ] Library view reading from IndexedDB\n- [ ] Reader view rendering sanitized HTML\n- [ ] Search with Fuse.js\n- [ ] Light/dark theme\n\n### Phase 3 — Polish & Ship\n- [ ] Error states for all failure modes\n- [ ] Delete flow\n- [ ] Keyboard accessibility basics (focus management, tab order)\n- [ ] Test on 20+ real-world sites (news, blogs, docs, forums, wikis)\n- [ ] Package for Chrome Web Store or local install\n\n---\n\n## 10. Dependencies\n\n| Package | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `@mozilla/readability` | Article extraction |\n| `dompurify` | HTML sanitization |\n| `idb` | IndexedDB wrapper |\n| `html-react-parser` | Render HTML in React |\n| `fuse.js` | Client-side search |\n| `react` / `react-dom` / `react-router-dom` | UI |\n| `tailwindcss` | Styling |\n\nSeven dependencies total. Small surface area.",
